<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Tomato Truss Sling for Heavy Fruit</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Heavy tomato clusters can snap trusses surprisingly easily, especially on high-yield or indeterminate plants.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most home gardeners, the best tomato truss sling is a soft, adjustable support that holds the fruit cluster without cutting into the stem.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    When tomatoes start producing larger or more concentrated fruit clusters, the weight can pull downward on the truss. Without support, this can lead to bending, splitting, or complete breakage.
  </p>
  <p>
    A truss sling supports the fruit directly, reducing stress on the plant and helping you keep more of the harvest intact.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: What Kind of Sling Works Best?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> soft fabric or mesh slings that distribute weight evenly.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for ease of use:</strong> adjustable slings that can be repositioned.</li>
      <li><strong>Avoid:</strong> rigid or thin supports that can cut into stems.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The goal is to support the fruit without stressing the plant.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Tomato Trusses Fail Under Heavy Fruit</h2>

  <p>
    Tomato trusses are designed to hold fruit, but not always at the size or density modern varieties can produce. Large clusters or beefsteak varieties can put more strain on the stem than it can handle.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is especially common in greenhouse or high-input setups where plants grow vigorously and produce heavily.
  </p>

  <p>
    Supporting the fruit early prevents damage later.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When You Actually Need a Truss Sling</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Large fruit varieties:</strong> beefsteak or heirloom types.</li>
    <li><strong>Heavy cluster formation:</strong> multiple fruits per truss.</li>
    <li><strong>Vertical growing systems:</strong> where plants are trained upward.</li>
    <li><strong>Greenhouse growing:</strong> where yields are higher.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Not every tomato needs support, but when fruit load increases, the risk of breakage rises quickly.
  </p>
</section>

