<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Use a Truss Sling Properly</h2>

  <ol class="plainList">
    <li>Place the sling under the fruit cluster.</li>
    <li>Attach it to your support system above the plant.</li>
    <li>Adjust tension so the weight is lifted slightly.</li>
    <li>Avoid pulling too tightly against the stem.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    The sling should support, not restrict, the plant.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Waiting Too Long</h3>
  <p>
    Once a truss is already stressed or bent, it is harder to correct without damage.
  </p>

  <h3>Using Thin or Rigid Supports</h3>
  <p>
    These can create pressure points that damage the stem.
  </p>

  <h3>Over-tightening</h3>
  <p>
    The sling should carry weight, not compress the plant.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Truss Sling vs Other Support Methods</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Plant clips:</strong> support stems, not fruit weight directly.</li>
    <li><strong>Cages:</strong> provide general support but not targeted truss relief.</li>
    <li><strong>Strings/hooks:</strong> support vertical growth, not heavy clusters.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Truss slings are specifically for fruit support, which other systems do not handle well on their own.
  </p>
</section>

